WEBVTT

00:11.160 --> 00:18.240
The Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction today presented by the

00:18.240 --> 00:20.460
Permian Basin Science Fiction Association.

00:23.760 --> 00:26.900
This is David Cruz, Daryl Lane, and David Carson.

00:31.980 --> 00:33.860
The subject of this show is space exploration.

00:35.380 --> 00:40.360
We're putting two limitations on that subject. One, that the exploration be outside the solar

00:40.360 --> 00:45.060
system, and two, that the story or novel we discuss involve the process of searching or

00:45.060 --> 00:48.860
exploring primarily, not simply the result of the exploration.

00:49.760 --> 00:53.360
And especially with those limitations, I think we have perhaps the purest of all science

00:53.360 --> 00:58.340
fiction themes or plots. Man's history on this planet has been a process of searching,

00:58.540 --> 01:03.420
discovering, then taming or civilizing. The discovery of the New World, for instance,

01:03.720 --> 01:08.240
was the result of a deliberate act of search by various European explorers, culminating

01:08.240 --> 01:15.080
with Columbus. The American West, as discovered and mapped by Lewis and Clark, is a classic

01:15.080 --> 01:22.220
example of exploration. Now, space, or our galaxy, the universe, is simply the next area

01:22.220 --> 01:27.980
to explore and discover and tame. I think the importance and purity of the theme lies in

01:27.980 --> 01:32.760
the notion that searching and discovering is the very essence of human nature. It's

01:32.760 --> 01:35.920
at the center of our survival instinct. Without it, we wouldn't be human.

01:37.320 --> 01:42.020
We've conquered the frontiers of Earth, and now we're ready to confront, we must confront,

01:42.760 --> 01:45.900
what one influential science fiction production is called the final frontier.

02:37.860 --> 02:43.600
Star Trek first came on the air in 1966 and continued through 1969 with 78 episodes being

02:43.600 --> 02:48.720
completed for the series. The show had several major science fiction authors writing for it,

02:48.760 --> 02:53.780
including Harlan Ellison, Theodore Sturgeon, and David Gerald. It would be hard to think of a

02:53.780 --> 03:00.840
better example of the space exploration theme. I think Star Trek epitomizes that because episode

03:00.840 --> 03:05.180
after episode, you saw the members of, crew members of the Enterprise confront aliens,

03:06.780 --> 03:12.480
all sorts of problems in a hostile universe, but they kept going, their spirit, their courage,

03:12.660 --> 03:19.400
their desire to go beyond mankind's limits almost. It carried the show for a long time,

03:19.480 --> 03:24.520
and I think it sort of is the essence of the space exploration theme, for pure exploration's sake.

03:24.920 --> 03:29.480
It was a fairly popular show when it was on the air, but it gained in popularity considerably

03:29.480 --> 03:34.740
after it went off the air and went into syndication. Conventions are held, Star Trek conventions,

03:35.020 --> 03:40.920
and it eventually spawned a movie. Well fitting in with your parameters on space exploration,

03:41.300 --> 03:46.900
we never saw the Enterprise going on a particular mission to do something in particular. It was

03:46.900 --> 03:53.280
always just out there exploring, and with no particular thing in mind, and whatever happened

03:53.280 --> 03:58.740
to it seemed to happen by accident, or just, it just happened. They were out there in an alien

03:58.740 --> 04:03.320
ship advanced upon them, or they found some planet with a distress signal calling out,

04:03.580 --> 04:08.380
but they were never really going to any particular place as far as we were told.

04:08.960 --> 04:13.360
I believe that really is kind of covered in the preamble to the show, where William Shatner says

04:13.360 --> 04:20.060
they're on that five-year mission to explore new planets and discover what's out there.

04:20.800 --> 04:24.400
I think that has to be one of the reasons the show is so popular again, because simply it

04:26.360 --> 04:33.080
satisfies people's need for the unknown, for the search, for the exploration, to seek something

04:33.080 --> 04:40.580
which is mysterious, which is unknown. It's simply caught the imagination, I think, of more than

04:42.280 --> 04:46.200
pure science fiction fans. I think everybody was fascinated with that kind of theme.

04:46.920 --> 04:51.340
I think this is especially shown in the episode called The Side of Paradise.

04:53.080 --> 04:58.620
Yes, I think they did that theme a number of times, or not a number, but every so often. I think

04:58.620 --> 05:06.080
that particular episode is the best expression of it, but they advanced to this particular planet

05:07.360 --> 05:13.160
and beamed down as they did on their transporters. There was a particular planet on this planet that

05:13.160 --> 05:19.200
shot spores whenever one of the crew members got near it. These spores would seemingly

05:21.440 --> 05:29.660
cause a state of total happiness, total contentment in the individual. He didn't have a sense of

05:29.660 --> 05:35.920
a goal. He didn't want to strive. He simply wanted to stagnate. I'm reminded of the poem by

05:35.920 --> 05:41.920
Tennis and the Lotus Eaters, where the crew of Ulysses ate the lotus plant and wanted to stay on

05:41.920 --> 05:47.680
the island forever without moving, without striving, without trying. Kirk, the captain,

05:47.820 --> 05:54.560
Captain Kirk is one of the few who was not infected by the spores. With the power of his

05:54.560 --> 06:01.360
personality, his cleverness, he is able to overturn the influence these spores have had

06:01.360 --> 06:07.940
in his crew members. I think the significance of it is that they are going to continue. They're

06:07.940 --> 06:12.640
not satisfied. They're not content. They would have been perfectly happy to live the rest of

06:12.640 --> 06:17.960
their existence on this planet. It was sort of an Eden, a paradise, but that's not enough for

06:17.960 --> 06:22.960
people. They need a goal. They need something to strive for, or they're not human. Kirk is able to

06:23.740 --> 06:26.900
get the crew members back to their original states and the enterprise goes on.

